<%= form_for(@user) do |f| %>
<div style="width:100%;">
  
  <% if @user.errors.any? %>
    <div id="error_explanation">
      <h2>Please correct <%= pluralize(@user.errors.count, "very minor error") %>…</h2>

      <ul>
      <% @user.errors.full_messages.each do |message| %>
        <li><%= message %></li>
      <% end %>
      </ul>
      
      <div class="field">
    <div class="email-input-float">
      <p style="margin-bottom: 10px; font-weight: bold;">Your E-mail</p>
      <%= f.text_field :email, :class => "input200" %></div>
    <div class="clear"></div>
  </div>

  <div style="margin: 10px auto; padding: 10px 0px; border-top: 1px dotted #000000; border-bottom: 1px dotted #000000;">
  <p style="margin-bottom: 10px; font-weight: bold;">Your Password / Pass Phrase</p>
  <div class="field">
    <div class="email-input-float"><%= f.password_field :password, :class => "input170", :placeholder => "Enter new password…" %></div>
    <div class="email-input-float" style="padding-top: 10px;"> + </div>
    <div class="email-input-float"><%= f.password_field :password_confirmation, :class => "input170", :placeholder => "Confirm new password…" %></div>
    <div class="clear"></div>
  </div>
  </div>
  <div class="actions">
    <button type="submit" class="blueformbutton">Save Changes</button>
  </div>
      
    </div>
  <% end %>
  
  <div class="error-explainer"><h2>Do Not Panic About 11-Character Passwords…</h2>
<p>They are actually easier to remember for humans, as well as more secure. 
<a href="http://xkcd.com/936/">This cartoon</a> explains it well. 
And this <a href="http://rumkin.com/tools/password/passchk.php">password strength tool</a> shows you and explains a bit more.
The upshot is that you get to choose a <strong>simple human pass phrase</strong> instead of a random and very confusing group of letters generated by a computer.
</p>
<p>
Instead of struggling to remember "mR9LVrsZ$%", you can do:
<br /><br />- "$400 Chorizo Is Expensive"
<br />- "Rajoy is a 1st class #####!!"
<br />- etc.
</p>
<p>
Be as creative as you like.
</p>
</div>

<div class="clear"></div>

  
  
</div>
<% end %>